which launched a couple of years ago on Steam

33
00:01:23,626 --> 00:01:25,987
and launched on PS4 and Xbox in December.

34
00:01:28,853 --> 00:01:34,220
I started working about 2015 and on our side US dollars around 2.5 million in revenue.

35
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:38,245
We also had a cool cake that was made in ultimate chicken horse style.

36
00:01:39,246 --> 00:01:41,268
And we're also five full-time staff members.

37
00:01:41,328 --> 00:01:44,693
So pretty similar looking studios from the onset.

38
00:01:46,056 --> 00:01:50,958
So I propose this talk partially because I think survivorship bias is rampant in the

39
00:01:51,018 --> 00:01:52,458
business development community.

40
00:01:53,318 --> 00:01:57,680
It often makes us act like our methods are the one true way to do business and if we

41
00:01:57,720 --> 00:01:59,961
succeed that is the correct way to do things.

42
00:02:00,881 --> 00:02:06,383
Some of you are probably here hoping to hear some steps to follow in order to make your

43
00:02:06,523 --> 00:02:09,604
first million dollars and unfortunately that's not going to happen.

44
00:02:10,815 --> 00:02:14,857
This is not a talk about what to do or a formula to apply.

45
00:02:15,497 --> 00:02:17,779
There are lots of different successful strategies.

46
00:02:18,179 --> 00:02:20,900
And although our studios have a lot in common,

47
00:02:20,920 --> 00:02:23,502
we're both commercial indies, we're both based in Montreal,

48
00:02:23,522 --> 00:02:24,743
we're both around the same size,

49
00:02:24,763 --> 00:02:25,803
it started around the same time,

50
00:02:26,504 --> 00:02:29,105
even so we have very fundamentally different ways

51
00:02:29,145 --> 00:02:30,546
of running our studio successfully.

52
00:02:31,126 --> 00:02:33,988
So the point is not to follow either of us.

53
00:02:35,149 --> 00:02:39,092
at all. We're going to walk you through our thought processes so that you can inspect

54
00:02:39,212 --> 00:02:43,435
your strategies and make your own decisions that are best for you. Okay?

55
00:02:45,287 --> 00:02:48,548
So we're going to go through what goals our studios have,

56
00:02:48,568 --> 00:02:51,988
how that impacted how we diversified our development

57
00:02:52,068 --> 00:02:55,949
or not, our burn rates, our revenue, and our projections.

58
00:02:55,969 --> 00:02:58,610
We're going to get very deep into the numbers of things

59
00:02:58,750 --> 00:03:02,070
as much as our business partners will allow.

60
00:03:02,950 --> 00:03:06,511
And we'll see what differences and similarities we can find.

61
00:03:08,451 --> 00:03:11,712
So why do our studios exist?

62
00:03:11,772 --> 00:03:12,932
I mean, OK, we want to make games.

63
00:03:13,918 --> 00:03:14,398
apparently.

64
00:03:15,898 --> 00:03:17,339
And what are we trying to achieve?

65
00:03:17,919 --> 00:03:20,059
As we put together this talk, we did realize that our goals

66
00:03:20,139 --> 00:03:21,240
are very much the same.

67
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:24,740
We wrote them out separately, but then they actually were

68
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:26,301
kind of actually the same goals.

69
00:03:27,741 --> 00:03:31,282
So when we started looking at these studio overall goals, we

70
00:03:31,322 --> 00:03:32,462
noticed that they're very similar.

71
00:03:32,482 --> 00:03:34,763
So we're going to break them down a little bit and sort of

72
00:03:34,783 --> 00:03:35,223
run through these.

73
00:03:35,903 --> 00:03:39,209
So at Clever Endeavor we want to make sure that our employees are always developing in

74
00:03:39,249 --> 00:03:45,400
terms of their skill and that we feel that they're growing as individuals in their skills

75
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:48,265
and in their work throughout the work that they're doing with us.

76
00:03:49,305 --> 00:03:54,407
Yeah, I would actually say that improved skills or craftsmanship, as we call it, and personal

77
00:03:54,447 --> 00:03:58,309
growth are really important to Kid Fox, maybe the most important at this point.

78
00:03:58,969 --> 00:04:03,131
We really do want to make some of the best games that exist, and that ambition means

79
00:04:03,151 --> 00:04:05,592
that with each game we have to keep raising the bar a little bit.

80
00:04:06,232 --> 00:04:08,355
We actually didn't discover this goal at first.

81
00:04:08,435 --> 00:04:10,298
We didn't think of it on day one.

82
00:04:10,618 --> 00:04:13,022
We kind of realized after we finished Moon Hunters

83
00:04:13,843 --> 00:04:15,305
that we had this ambition, and we

84
00:04:15,365 --> 00:04:16,607
felt we could realize it together.

85
00:04:16,707 --> 00:04:19,551
So now part of what we're going to be talking about

86
00:04:19,571 --> 00:04:22,935
are plans to enable this self-improvement and this team

87
00:04:22,995 --> 00:04:23,696
growth together.

88
00:04:25,497 --> 00:04:27,879
And now one of our first goals from the very beginning

89
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:30,521
was to treat ourselves like professionals,

90
00:04:30,942 --> 00:04:32,383
but also to take care of ourselves.

91
00:04:32,763 --> 00:04:37,006
So we do occasional overtime, but in the past years,

92
00:04:37,187 --> 00:04:38,808
we've never worked on the weekends,

93
00:04:39,448 --> 00:04:41,130
and we've never had sustained overtime.

94
00:04:41,150 --> 00:04:43,772
I personally, as the captain of the ship,

95
00:04:43,852 --> 00:04:45,914
say you're not allowed to work on Kit Fox stuff

96
00:04:45,954 --> 00:04:46,614
after a certain hour.

97
00:04:46,634 --> 00:04:47,695
Feel free to work on your own stuff.

98
00:04:48,635 --> 00:04:55,417
And we work smart pictured here are the original four co-founders of kitfox although Mike is no longer at kitfox

99
00:04:55,457 --> 00:04:58,098
we still miss him and

100
00:04:58,538 --> 00:04:59,539
On our end we're in the same boat

101
00:04:59,659 --> 00:05:06,461
we look a little bit different than them, but we also try to avoid overtime and crunch pretty vehemently and

102
00:05:06,761 --> 00:05:09,381
We want to be able to work on the things that we want to work on

103
00:05:09,942 --> 00:05:14,003
obviously, but that leads to a better quality of life and we want to

104
00:05:14,419 --> 00:05:17,861
take careful attention to make sure that our employees and the partners themselves,

105
00:05:18,341 --> 00:05:20,042
our lives come first before our work.

106
00:05:20,222 --> 00:05:22,363
So if there are issues, if there's whatever things come up,

107
00:05:23,283 --> 00:05:26,064
we know that the priority is on our lives and our stress

108
00:05:26,104 --> 00:05:28,825
and our situation before our work directly.

109
00:05:30,647 --> 00:05:32,087
The next thing is sustainability.

110
00:05:32,167 --> 00:05:33,408
Of course, we want to survive.

111
00:05:34,629 --> 00:05:36,469
So our goal as a company is to become

112
00:05:36,509 --> 00:05:38,250
a long-term sustainable company

113
00:05:38,290 --> 00:05:39,491
that can survive for many years,

114
00:05:39,751 --> 00:05:40,832
pay competitive salaries.

115
00:05:41,552 --> 00:05:42,792
Like we talked about, skill development,

116
00:05:43,073 --> 00:05:44,533
have our employees develop their skills.

117
00:05:45,294 --> 00:05:47,675
We never really had the goal of growing a company

118
00:05:47,695 --> 00:05:50,496
to become huge and flipping it, selling it,

119
00:05:50,556 --> 00:05:51,437
and then starting something new.

120
00:05:51,457 --> 00:05:52,797
That's not really the way we see it.

121
00:05:53,177 --> 00:05:56,199
It's more of a long-term, slow, steady rise.

122
00:05:57,059 --> 00:05:57,960
Yeah, it was the same for us.

123
00:05:58,020 --> 00:06:00,701
We put survival as a number one priority.

124
00:06:00,781 --> 00:06:03,343
I wanted Kit Fox to exist in five or 10 years,

125
00:06:03,363 --> 00:06:05,384
and now it's been five years, so goal one achieved.

126
00:06:06,465 --> 00:06:08,026
And so in many ways, this did translate

127
00:06:08,066 --> 00:06:11,588
into safer, less risky, more conservative business

128
00:06:11,688 --> 00:06:12,748
development practices.

129
00:06:13,529 --> 00:06:16,150
The primary of which is actually that we

130
00:06:16,231 --> 00:06:19,372
felt diversifying our studio into developing

131
00:06:19,432 --> 00:06:20,873
multiple different kinds of products

132
00:06:21,314 --> 00:06:23,615
was what was best for us and our goals.

133
00:06:24,675 --> 00:06:30,737
So this decision of whether or not to diversify into multiple products or to develop just one game at a time

134
00:06:31,477 --> 00:06:36,438
Does impact everything else it determines what your studio is good at?

135
00:06:37,319 --> 00:06:43,320
How it grows over time it's a cyclical thing or as soon as you start either diversifying or focusing on one game

136
00:06:44,100 --> 00:06:48,041
Your personnel changes your strategy for dealing with crises changes

137
00:06:48,822 --> 00:06:51,163
And of course you can change your goals midway.

138
00:06:52,023 --> 00:06:54,324
You can start to diversify after developing only one game.

139
00:06:54,344 --> 00:06:57,025
You can start to focus after deciding

140
00:06:57,065 --> 00:06:58,286
that diversifying was bad for you.

141
00:06:59,226 --> 00:07:03,068
But the way that you develop even your first project

142
00:07:03,988 --> 00:07:06,729
could change depending on how you want to orient

143
00:07:06,750 --> 00:07:07,930
your studio and its strengths.

144
00:07:11,143 --> 00:07:16,086
The short answer is that Kit Fox is very diversified oriented.

145
00:07:16,826 --> 00:07:19,547
Some successful studios diversify, such as Clay.

146
00:07:20,548 --> 00:07:22,649
Clay is one of my favorite game studios.

147
00:07:22,849 --> 00:07:24,089
And honestly, a lot of the advice

148
00:07:24,130 --> 00:07:26,270
I'm going to give you today is actually advice

149
00:07:26,291 --> 00:07:29,052
that Jamie Chang of Clay gave me back in 2013.

150
00:07:29,132 --> 00:07:31,593
And I immediately started trying to act on.

151
00:07:32,553 --> 00:07:34,694
Lots of game studios are happy to bet it all

152
00:07:34,754 --> 00:07:37,056
on one big release, especially they have.

153
00:07:38,196 --> 00:07:38,936
Nothing to lose.

154
00:07:39,557 --> 00:07:42,779
You're making your first game, why not make it your big only thing?

155
00:07:43,539 --> 00:07:47,901
But I preferred, again, to bet on survival and calculate our risks and

156
00:07:47,921 --> 00:07:48,762
take the safer bet.

157
00:07:49,302 --> 00:07:51,503
So when we were in the middle of developing Shattered Planet,

158
00:07:51,523 --> 00:07:57,286
I saw an announcement online that the Square Enix collective was going to exist.

159
00:07:58,448 --> 00:08:01,210
And there was no call for pitches or anything like that.

160
00:08:01,571 --> 00:08:04,173
I just cold emailed Square Enix saying,

161
00:08:04,213 --> 00:08:06,796
can I please pitch something to your weird new thing?

162
00:08:06,836 --> 00:08:08,057
And they said, I guess.

163
00:08:08,097 --> 00:08:10,099
I don't know who you are, but OK.

164
00:08:10,720 --> 00:08:12,241
You have to get it in by Friday, though.

165
00:08:13,262 --> 00:08:15,484
So we hadn't even soft launched.

166
00:08:16,145 --> 00:08:17,867
our first game yet, Shattered Planet.

167
00:08:17,887 --> 00:08:20,990
We had four people, and when I told the team,

168
00:08:21,030 --> 00:08:23,052
I was like, no, no, no, let's stop for two days,

169
00:08:23,252 --> 00:08:25,534
make a pitch document, and send it to these randos.

170
00:08:25,935 --> 00:08:27,516
They were like, what are you doing?

171
00:08:27,797 --> 00:08:30,079
We're behind schedule, we have assets to make.

172
00:08:31,220 --> 00:08:34,043
And our business partners also, our investors,

173
00:08:34,643 --> 00:08:37,366
said maybe you should be focusing a little bit more, Tanya.

174
00:08:37,386 --> 00:08:38,727
This is a recurring theme with me.

175
00:08:40,870 --> 00:08:44,034
It worked out. We actually pitched the Moon Hunters, which was our next game,

176
00:08:44,134 --> 00:08:46,016
and it was actually a really great opportunity for us.

177
00:08:46,076 --> 00:08:49,640
And we had no way of knowing that at the time, but we decided it was worth risking two days

178
00:08:50,141 --> 00:08:54,206
to explore this new opportunity for diversification, because I had already known

179
00:08:54,226 --> 00:08:58,411
that I wanted to be developing multiple projects in parallel as much as possible.

180
00:08:59,252 --> 00:09:01,813
So over time, Kid Fox has become maximally diversified,

181
00:09:01,833 --> 00:09:03,794
like maybe way too diversified, actually.

182
00:09:04,455 --> 00:09:06,596
In five years, we've released three major projects

183
00:09:06,776 --> 00:09:08,217
and we spent a year on work for hire.

184
00:09:09,497 --> 00:09:11,298
And 2018 marks our very first time

185
00:09:11,578 --> 00:09:14,300
with two games solidly in production together,

186
00:09:14,880 --> 00:09:17,461
even though I was just here on Monday

187
00:09:17,862 --> 00:09:19,302
talking about how Moon Hunters

188
00:09:19,342 --> 00:09:20,843
had initially disappointing sales.

189
00:09:21,985 --> 00:09:26,471
So there's good and bad sides of diversifying and developing

190
00:09:26,511 --> 00:09:28,473
multiple games at once.

191
00:09:28,974 --> 00:09:31,717
I mean, sure, yeah, it's lower risk, obviously.

192
00:09:32,418 --> 00:09:35,883
If one project does well, we can split it up

193
00:09:35,943 --> 00:09:37,304
into multiple other things.

194
00:09:37,344 --> 00:09:39,828
And if no single failure can close the studio.

195
00:09:40,789 --> 00:09:43,450
And because we're having multiple little revenue streams,

196
00:09:44,050 --> 00:09:46,111
things are generally more stable.

197
00:09:46,651 --> 00:09:49,153
We don't need to rely on one individual sale.

198
00:09:50,233 --> 00:09:52,874
Of course, it's still a little spiky because Steam,

199
00:09:53,175 --> 00:09:56,656
but more games equals a stronger back catalog

200
00:09:56,896 --> 00:09:59,458
and steadier flow, and I sleep better at night.

201
00:10:00,534 --> 00:10:03,255
And our team members are quite flexible now

202
00:10:03,295 --> 00:10:05,096
because they've worked on lots of different projects together

203
00:10:05,236 --> 00:10:07,077
in lots of different configurations.

204
00:10:08,017 --> 00:10:10,798
Hybrid team members stay more excited and refreshed

205
00:10:10,818 --> 00:10:12,359
because they're not working the same thing

206
00:10:12,399 --> 00:10:13,279
for years and years and years.

207
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:15,700
And so people are less likely, I think,

208
00:10:15,820 --> 00:10:18,541
to feel cynical or bitter on a project

209
00:10:18,581 --> 00:10:20,062
because they know they have other options.

210
00:10:20,282 --> 00:10:23,123
And if there isn't one right now, there probably will be soon.

211
00:10:24,124 --> 00:10:25,504
So we can adjust to change

212
00:10:25,564 --> 00:10:27,565
according to team members' interests pretty quickly.

213
00:10:28,813 --> 00:10:30,074
And with a large number of projects,

214
00:10:30,134 --> 00:10:32,757
we can experience a very junior team member

215
00:10:32,777 --> 00:10:34,619
can join in straight from school

216
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:36,761
and experience from pre-production

217
00:10:36,821 --> 00:10:38,944
all the way to shipping very quickly

218
00:10:39,144 --> 00:10:41,426
because they can see the whole life cycle

219
00:10:41,627 --> 00:10:43,228
of a project happening right next to them.

220
00:10:44,069 --> 00:10:45,491
So there's a lot of different opportunities

221
00:10:45,511 --> 00:10:46,071
from start to finish.

222
00:10:46,592 --> 00:10:50,833
Unfortunately, hybrid team members are also not particularly specialists.

223
00:10:50,873 --> 00:10:52,533
I mean, this is no new problem in indie.

224
00:10:52,593 --> 00:10:54,613
We're all kind of wearing a lot of hats.

225
00:10:55,654 --> 00:11:00,575
But this is another thing altogether when you are doing something

226
00:11:00,595 --> 00:11:03,495
completely different on a different kind of project every year or so.

227
00:11:03,515 --> 00:11:06,056
I mean, at this point, we have specialized a little bit

228
00:11:06,076 --> 00:11:08,517
into system-driven RPGs, I guess.

229
00:11:09,737 --> 00:11:11,857
But the art styles are all over the place,

230
00:11:11,917 --> 00:11:13,318
the technology is all over the place.

231
00:11:13,538 --> 00:11:15,698
So you can't say, like, we have the world's best.

232
00:11:16,519 --> 00:11:19,841
person at anything. They're the best at making that one game that one time.

233
00:11:21,503 --> 00:11:29,129
And we also start projects constantly. Thankfully, I like coming up with new ideas. I don't really

234
00:11:29,189 --> 00:11:35,655
mind having blank pages all the time, but it is a little bit stressful to say, oh,

235
00:11:35,675 --> 00:11:38,557
we got to start again every year and a half or so.

236
00:11:39,577 --> 00:11:41,138
But at least it's better than finishing projects.

237
00:11:41,178 --> 00:11:43,498
Finishing projects is the worst.

238
00:11:44,338 --> 00:11:47,259
I mean, I don't know how many of you have survived a game.

239
00:11:47,339 --> 00:11:48,939
Games are terrible to finish.

240
00:11:49,940 --> 00:11:51,540
And diversification makes that worse

241
00:11:51,580 --> 00:11:53,761
because every time you shut down one crisis,

242
00:11:53,801 --> 00:11:55,301
there's another one coming in the door.

243
00:11:56,701 --> 00:12:00,962
So we do have regular upending of priorities and tasks.

244
00:12:01,462 --> 00:12:04,943
The good news being that we definitely have to prioritize.

245
00:12:06,469 --> 00:12:12,310
well, but as the director, I mean, I still do end up with more difficult decisions per

246
00:12:12,410 --> 00:12:12,750
week.

247
00:12:13,871 --> 00:12:19,612
Last fall, we were actually shipping the Shrouded Isle while also hiring up for Boyfriend Dungeon

248
00:12:20,512 --> 00:12:25,653
and shipping Moon Hunters on Switch, and also our tech lead was doing R&D on his own personal

249
00:12:25,693 --> 00:12:28,294
project, so we had like four projects for six people.

250
00:12:28,314 --> 00:12:30,114
Not ideal.

251
